#Harvey update for Fort Bend County.

Important info: As you know, according to both Fort Bend County and National Weather Service officials, the Brazos River, which is located near Memorial Hermann Sugar Land Hospital, continues to see increasing water levels that are posing a severe flooding threat to the immediate area.  As a proactive measure to ensure everyone’s continued safety and in consultation with local and national officials, Memorial Hermann Sugar Land will temporarily close its doors until further notice. Patients currently at Memorial Hermann Sugar Land will be safely transferred to Memorial Hermann Southwest Hospital at 7600 Beechnut, Houston, TX, 77074.  Memorial Hermann has prepared for events like today’s and has procedures in place to make this move as seamless as possible for our patients, families, employees and physician partners.  In coordination with CMOC (the Catastrophic Medical Operations Center), they will begin transferring patients this afternoon.

UPDATE ON U.S. Small Business Administration CLAIMS: SBA has begun paying out Harvey disaster loans, but it can be confusing when folks only receive part of their approved loan. Folks should initially receive up to $25,000 of their loan, then receipts and/or invoices are needed for additional approval. Once approved, the rest of the loan should be issued. SBA defers all loan payments for 12 months from the date the loan is signed, so payment w/interest is not required initially. Please call my Pearland office at (281) 485-4855 if you need help with your SBA loan. My staff can answer questions and file an inquiry on your behalf if needed.

Proud to introduce the Preserving Rehabilitation Innovation Centers Act with my friend & colleague Gene Green. This bill recognizes top inpatient research-oriented rehabilitation hospitals for their work in helping patients. My statement here. → http://bit.ly/2nENXgG

The U.S. Small Business Administration has begun to pay out #Harvey disaster loans. Folks have expressed confusion about only receiving part of their approved loan. This should mean that you will receive the loan in several installments. However, in some cases folks are being told they need to start repaying their loan with interest as if they received the full amount. Please contact my Pearland office at (281) 485-4855 if you are having this problem. My staff will be more than happy to answer any questions you may have about this process and may be able to file an inquiry on your behalf.
